article.description: Britney Davis-White had a career-high 21 points and Chakhia Cole added 18 to help the Mountaineers stun Rutgers 56-40 in the Big East tournament semifinal.
article.headline: Mountaineers shock Rutgers in Big East tourney semi
article.linkText: Mountaineers shock Rutgers in Big East tourney semi
article.story:
HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- West Virginia limped into the Big East tournament without leading scorer Meg Bulger and an eight-game losing streak.

Now, after three straight upsets, the 12th-seeded Mountaineers are one victory away from their first title.

Britney Davis White scored a career-high 21 points and Chakhia Cole added 18 for the Mountaineers, who pulled off the biggest stunner Monday night with a 56-40 win over No. 6 Rutgers in the tournament semifinal.

"We lost eight in a row after Meg went down and really couldn't find our identity," West Virginia coach Mike Carey said. "But right now I've never been prouder of a group of girls to really regroup and do the things they've done in this tournament."

The Mountaineers (15-15) are the lowest seed to reach the tournament finals in its 23-year history. The top-seeded Scarlet Knights (25-4) have won the last two regular-season titles and were aiming for their first tournament title. But the smaller, scrappy Mountaineers foiled those plans with their third upset in as many days and held Rutgers, which was undefeated in the conference for the first time in school history, to a season-low 40 points.

The Mountaineers, who are in the finals for the first time in school history, play Connecticut in Tuesday's final.

"I think we did come in with a little bit of a chip on our shoulder," Cole said. "We came out and did what we wanted to do. For everybody who counted us out, we are still here."

West Virginia knocked off fifth-seeded Louisville 54-45 on Saturday then beat fourth-seeded St. John's 55-49 on Sunday. Bulger was averaging 19.8 points a game when she suffered a season-ending knee injury in a Jan. 29 loss at St. John's. West Virginia won its next game but ended their season with an eight-game losing streak.

Cappie Pondexter, the conference player of the year, finished with 21 points for Rutgers. She scored the last eight points for the Scarlet Knights over a four-minute span. But the Mountaineers got to the line on nearly ever possession and made 10-of-13 free throws
down the stretch to seal the game.

"Our intensity never picked up," Pondexter said. "It was obvious they wanted it more. We didn't play like we wanted to win. This chapter is closed and there is nothing we can do about it. We have to move on and get ready for NCAAs."

The Scarlet Knights, tops in the nation in defense, had a chance to get back into it midway through the second half. Matee Ajavon scored off her own steal and got the Scarlet Knights to within seven at 35-28. Pondexter stole the ball on the next possession and hit a floater off the breakaway that would have cut the lead to five, but the basket was ruled no good. Rutgers' Essence Carson trailed the play and was called for interference when she leaped
and hit the rim as the ball dropped through. The Scarlet Knights would get no closer after that.

"I think [West Virginia] played with a great deal of heart and determination," Rutgers coach C. Vivian Stringer said. "They were small, but they fought hard. I don't know if we overlooked them, but there is no point complaining about it. We deserved to lose."

Cole and Davis-White, as they have all tournament, played with passion, determined to keep their season alive.

The 5-foot-10 Cole battled inside all game against Rutgers bigger post players Kia Vaughn, Michelle Campbell and Mariota Theodoris. Most of her points came on driving layups. Davis-White was 14-for-20 from the line, making most of them in the final two minutes of the game.

The Mountaineers also had most of crowd behind them in the second half. Thousands of UConn fans who arrived early before the UConn-DePaul late semifnal quickly threw their allegiance to the Mountaineers and roared with each Mountaineer basket. The Scarlet Knights had swept the Huskies this season, denying UConn a share of the regular-season title. The Mountaineers drew a standing ovation in the closing seconds when they finally had the game in hand.

"It was kind of different for us. The crowd was there and it was big," said Olayinka Sanni, who finished with six rebounds, three blocked shots and three steals for West Virginia. "It was just a great atmosphere to play here at Connecticut, where there is history and to come here and do what we had to do."
